Introduction

This analysis explores flight data that includes arrival and departure details, carriers, arrival and departure delays, reasons for delays, etc, for all commercial flights within the USA, from January to April 2008. This database contains scheduled and actual departure and arrival times reported by certified U.S. air carriers that account for at least one percent of domestic scheduled passenger revenues. The data is collected by the Office of Airline Information, Bureau of Transportation Statistics (BTS).The data consists of 2389217 records in total and the datasets are available for download from: https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/HG7NV7

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 2389217 entries with fliight information from 3 January 2008 to 17 April 2008. There are 29 features in the original dataset but in this investigation I will be using atmost 23 variables. Most variables in this dataset are numeric except 'UniqueCarrier, TailNum, Origin, Dest and CancellationCode'

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest will be the days, time, destinations, delays and cancellations as I am mostly interested in finding the worst and best times for flights with regards to flight delays and cancellations.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Dayofmonth, DayOfWeek, DepTime, ArrTime, Cancelled and all the Delay variables will help the most in supporting the investigation

In [15]:
def days_distribution(df):
    """ 
    Function takes in a dataframe and prints 2 visualisations side by side

    Args:
        df = dataframe
    Returns:
        2 Bar charts side by side, of DayofMonth distribution and DayOfWeek distribution,
          which are variables of the original flight data
    """

    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    plt.figure(figsize=[20, 5])
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    sb.countplot(data=df, x='DayofMonth', color=base_color)
    plt.title('On-time flights per DayofMonth')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Flights');

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    p = sb.countplot(data=df, x='DayOfWeek', color=base_color)
    plt.title('On-time flights per DayOfWeek')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Flights');
    days = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']
    p.set(xticklabels = days);
In [16]:
days_distribution(df_2008)

31 January and 31 March had the lowest number of flights and overally Saturdays recorded the fewest flights followed by Sundays

In [17]:
def overall_carriers(df):
    """
    Function displays the overall number of flights for each airline of the given dataframe,
     using the 'UniqueCarrier' variable

    Args:
        df = dataframe 
    Returns:
        An ordered Bar chart of airlines with their total number of flights  
    """

    plt.figure(figsize=(22, 10))
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    carriers = df['UniqueCarrier'].value_counts()
    sb.barplot(carriers.index, carriers.values, color='blue')
    bins = df.shape[0]
    plt.xlabel('Airline Code')
    plt.ylabel('Flights')
    plt.title('Overall number of flights per Airline',fontsize=18)    # Default title

To start off, I will look at the distributions of Delayed flights and how they compare to the overall distributions of all flights.

In [27]:
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 16))
n_points = df_2008.shape[0]
for i, j in enumerate(['Year', 'Month', 'DayofMonth', 'DayOfWeek']):
    plt.subplot(2, 2, i+1)

    gen_counts = df_2008[j].value_counts()
    delayed_gen_counts = delayed_flights[j].value_counts()

    gen_counts.sort_index().plot.barh(label='Overall', width=.6)
    delayed_gen_counts.sort_index().plot.barh(label='Delayed', color='purple')

    locs, labels = plt.yticks()
    for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):
        count = gen_counts[int(label.get_text())]
        delayed_count = delayed_gen_counts[int(label.get_text())]
        pct = f'{100*delayed_count/count:0.1f}%'
        plt.text(0.30*count, loc, pct, ha='center', color='w')

    plt.legend(framealpha=0.5, fancybox=True)
    plt.title(f'Number of Flights per {j}')

February and Fridays had the highest proportion of delays. April and Wednesdays had the lowest delays.

Multivariate Exploration

In this section, I will explore further on other relationships involving delays to get a clearer picture on the best and worst time for flights.

           'Late Aircraft Delay', 'NAS Delay', 'Security Delay'])
plt.xlabel('Delay Time')
plt.ylabel('Air Time')
plt.scatter(data=delayed_flights.sample(10000),
            x='SecurityDelay', y='AirTime', alpha=1/2)
plt.legend(labels=['Weather Delay', 'Carrier Delay',
           'Late Aircraft Delay', 'NAS Delay', 'Security Delay'])
plt.xlabel('Delay Time')
plt.ylabel('Air Time');

Flights with all air times had experienced security delays although it was only for a few minutes. A higher delay time was common to flights with an air time of less than 300 minutes.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

I observed the carrier delays were experienced on Saturdays, this was interesting since I had previously observed that Saturdays had recorded the fewest flights in overall among all the days of the week.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Most overall delays were experienced on Fridays and they turned out to be mostly due to late aircraft delays.
